<br>
My friends, it has been many moons since I have last spoken with you and much has happened in my life. I feel it is best to start where I left off…<br>
<br>
After arriving in Shadowhaven, I spent the next months wandering the streets without purpose. I didn’t know what to do or what my soul required for me to be at peace so I continued to wander Shadowhaven and the Bazaar searching yet not knowing what I was searching for. At the end of 2 months, things were looking bad. My meager funds were running out, and without my studies to concentrate on, the depression from my fathers murder had returned.<br>
<br>
But one night changed everything for me. That night, I was visited by the great Ratha Sha’Naya, a Khati Sha and hero of my people. I was so ashamed of the path that my life had taken that I was unable to meet his steady gaze. Yet he spoke to me as a brother! He offered his help and made me feel that I was not alone in my situation. As he left, I heard a soft rustle at my window and turned with surprise to behold a beautiful maiden of a race I had never before seen. She introduced herself as Journai Fa’Wander – a Half Elf Ranger in the service of Tunare, and friend to all Vah Shir. As we talked, my surprise at meeting my first half-elf diminished and I could tell that this person was warm and genuinely concerned with the events of my life. On taking her leave of me, she also added her offer of assistance to those of the great Ratha. For the first time in many months I felt true friendship and compassion from these two great adventurers.<br>
<br>
That night I spent in deep soul-searching. The care shown me by Ratha and Journai made me ashamed of my months of idleness and for the first time made me set my life to a purpose. I decided that I must first find out all of the details of my father’s death and try to put his soul at peace. With this resolve, I set out the next day determined to find Trade Baron Ooblieth whom I had been assigned to as a diplomat before my attack, and speak with him about my father.<br>
<br>
This proved harder than I imagined. For days I searched the city and could find no trace of Ooblieth. Finally, stopping in The Lost Turnip Inn, my searches paid off. After a little conversation a few pints of ale and a couple gold pieces, the innkeeper revealed to me that around the time of my father’s death, Ooblieth had suffered some type of financial misfortune and was removed from his office by the High Council. Since then he had been seen consorting with many of the criminal inhabitants of the city. He told me that he had been seen working with a band of dwarvish pickpockets that frequented the bank area in the southern area of the city at night, hoping to catch unwary travelers off-guard. I thanked the innkeeper, paid my tab, and set out to find Ooblieth.<br>
<br>
I waited until dusk and crept silently towards the bank. My Vah Shir night vision and reflexes helped me move silently and swiftly towards my target and I concealed myself in the shadows of a neighboring building overlooking the bank. After a few minutes, I spotted the band of dwarvish pickpockets casually hidden among the crates and barrels of a neighboring bakery. Among them was a human who didn’t fit the image of a pickpocket. His clothes might have been considered fine once, but now they hung loosely off of him and were worn and stained with food and mud. The man was slightly overweight, yet his skin seemed to hang from him as if he had once been enormous, but had lost a great deal of weight lately. At first glance, Ooblieth looked like a typical lazy merchant, but his eyes gave him away. They were the cold, hard, calculating eyes of a criminal and they scanned the streets with an intensity that betrayed his appearance<br>
<br>
I waited patiently until morning when the pickpockets split up. I slipped out of the shadows and began to follow Ooblieth through the maze of alleys behind the stores of Shadowhaven, waiting for the perfect moment to reveal myself. At last, we passed into a deep alley where the light and sounds of the streets hardly penetrated. The musty smell of dirt and decay and the steady drip of water made this alley feel like an animal’s lair. Ooblieth was heading towards the far end where a pile of boxes and a stretched canvas tarp made a crude shelter but I sprang into action. I called upon the powers of the spirits to reach out from the netherworld and root Ooblieth in place. As the cold, spirit hands closed upon his legs, he screamed in fright and began to struggle for freedom. At that moment, I stepped out from the shadows and approached him. “You! But, but…you’re dead!”, Ooblieth gasped and struggled harder.<br>
<br>
Unbidden, a growl came from my throat and I flexed my claws and spoke with menace, “As you can see, I am far from dead. Tell me what you know of my attack and my father’s murder or the spirits of my people will make you wish for a quick death that I will not grant you”. Overcome with fear, Ooblieth slumped in the grip of the spirits and the light seemed to go out of his eyes. He then began to relate to me a story that filled me with a mixture of fear and rage.<br>
<br>
“As you know, I was once a Trade Barron in this city”, Ooblieth began. “No pleasures were denied me and everything was possible for a price. Power, money, women even the souls of Vah such as yourself. Despite this, there were still those more powerful than me. I was required to report to a member of the High Council, Agearoth and it was he that held the ability to revoke my trade license if he chose.” Ooblieth continued, “Upon first meeting Agearoth I could smell the scent of corruption about him. You see, those of us with the taint, can sense our own kind and are drawn to it. I tried bribery at first, but he saw through that and spoke plainly to me, ‘You may trade without reserve or fear of punishment, Ooblieth, and I don’t require your petty bribes. But one day I will need you to take care of a “problem” for me and you will do it or you will find yourself without more than just your trade license.’ When he said this, his eyes never changed – they remained cold and hard. I knew right away that no amount of money or influence would work on this man and my only choice was to agree to his proposal.” “About a year ago he again called me to his chambers and commanded me to perform a service for him. He explained that there was a young Vah Shir coming to Shadowhaven to be a liaison between me and Shar Vahl. As he said this, his eyes bored into me and held me in their grip, and as he continued, my blood ran cold. He told me that if you ever reached Shadowhaven, I would not survive the night. And so I arranged a little ‘accident’ for you.” “ We knew you would be coming through Shadeweaver’s Thicket, so we released a Saurek Darkclaw where we knew you would pass. Unfortunately I was required to bring Agearoth your head to prove your death, but when the Saurek didn’t return we assumed it had run off into the thicket to eat your corpse. No matter how many times I assured Agearoth you had been killed, without proof, he was enraged. He stripped me of my title, licence and property and sent me into the streets with the warning that if he ever saw me again, I would not survive.” “Shortly after this, I heard that there was an assassination attempt on Agearoth and he disappeared. I was too terrified to show my face around the Council Chambers to make sure but the rumors in the street say that he is now in hiding. So I have been on the streets ever since – eating from refuse piles, sleeping in the dirt and trying to steal a few silver to sleep in an inn again or have a warm meal.”<br>
<br>
His story complete, Ooblieth sagged in the grip of the spirits like a rag doll. “Go ahead and kill me Vulrath”, he said. “I would rather be dead than live like a rat in a pile of filth for the rest of my life.” Shaking with rage, I raised my hand and began to chant to the spirits. Ooblieth closed his eyes expecting the final blast of spiritual energy that would rend his body, but when I dropped my hand, the spiritual force holding him disappeared and he dropped to the ground in a heap. “I refuse to become what you are, Ooblieth.”, I said. “Your life now is punishment enough for the pain you have caused and your story has given me the information I need.” And without another word I turned away from the filth, back towards the streets of Shadowhaven to ponder my next move.<br>
